LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (especially Eastern Ulster; of Norman origin): habitational name from Graye in Calvados, France, named from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Graec(i)us</i>, meaning ‘Greek’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This is probably the chief source of the surname in Britain.","English: nickname for someone with gray hair or a gray beard, from Middle English <i>grey</i> (Old English <i>grǣg</i>, <i>grēg</i>) ‘gray’. In Ireland it has been used as a translation of various Gaelic surnames derived from <i>riabhach</i> ‘brindled, gray’, including <b>Mac Giolla Riabhaigh</b>; see   McGreevy  . In North America, this surname has assimilated names with similar meaning from other languages.","French: habitational name from Gray in Haute-Saône or Le Gray in Seine-Maritime."],"variants":[{"name":"McGreevy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Seamus, Brendan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Riabhaigh</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Riabhach</i> ‘brindled, grizzled’. Compare   Reavey   and   Creevy   2."]},{"name":"Grayer","meanings":["English (southern): nickname from Middle English <i>grei</i> ‘gray’ (see   Gray  ) + <i>her</i> ‘hair’.","Scottish (Ayrshire): variant of   Greer  ."]},{"name":"Grays","meanings":["English (Durham): variant of   Gray  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, or of   Grace  ."]},{"name":"Grice","meanings":["English (Midlands): from Middle English <i>grice</i>, <i>grise</i> ‘pig’ (Old Norse <i>gríss</i>), probably a nickname or a metonymic occupational name for a swineherd.","English: nickname for a gray-haired man, from Middle English <i>grice</i>, <i>gris</i> ‘gray’ (Old French <i>gris</i>, apparently of ancient Germanic origin, and probably a distant cognate of   Gray   1).","Possibly also an Americanized form of German   Greis  ."]},{"name":"Grey","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: variant of   Gray  .","German: dialect variant of   Grau  .","In some cases also an American shortened and altered form of Ukrainian <b>Grushko</b>: nickname or topographic name derived from a Russian-influenced transliteration of <i>grushka</i> ‘pear, pear tree’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Gray was born in 1200, his father, Baron Henry de Grey - Baron Grey of Codnor, was 24 and his mother, Isolda De Bardolf, was 18. He had at least 1 daughter with Joan Peyvere. He died in 1266, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1200–1266":"1200–1266","1218–1266":"1218–1266","1212–1256":"1212–1256","1255–1343":"1255–1343","1176–1219":"1176–1219","1182–1246":"1182–1246","1176":"1176","1182":"1182","abt 1255":"umbes 1255","8 September 1219":"8. september 1219","1246":"1246","1256":"1256","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","1266":"1266","1343":"1343","1255":"1255","1219":"1219","1218":"1218","Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, E